review:
Please provide a TABLET experience on iPad with the collapsible list of history on the left and chat on the right - similar to your desktop browser app. 2) while generating responses on the desktop browser, it pauses and keeps displaying ‚ÄúContinue generating responses‚Äù button for every few items/responses forcing to click the button repeatedly. During generation, there is a button to ‚ÄúStop generating responses‚Äù - if we need to stop, we can always click this button - there is no need to pause and ask us to click continue again and again which is a bad UX. 3) there is no way to delete individual chat items from a chat history list of items to clean up the list. 4) if I ask for ‚Äútop 20‚Äù, it generates just 10 answers and displays ‚Äúplease let me know if you‚Äôd like more ‚Äú but no option to generate more responses to the question. Either generate all 20 answers (ideally) or provide an option to continue generation.

Please provide options to delete questions from a history and also move questions/responses to another history. Please offer these features and I‚Äôll gladly give it 5 stars. Cheers!

review:
I appreciate the devs implementing Siri support‚Äîit is already enhancing the usefulness of the app, despite being a little clunky. I‚Äôd prefer if it were possible to make a query in one fell swoop, however. Currently, it seems like I have to say ‚Äúask ChatGPT‚Äù then wait to be asked what my query is before saying the actual query. I know that it‚Äôs possible in other contexts to submit a request to a third-party app through Siri in a single query‚ÄîI‚Äôm able to say ‚ÄúCreate a reminder for XYZ in Things,‚Äù for example. 

In addition, the responses produced when querying Siri seem identical to those you would get in-app. This isn‚Äôt actually ideal in a scenario when you‚Äôre getting a spoken response‚Äîthey just go on for way too long. I wonder if the app could be smart enough to recognize that a request was coming via Siri and then effectively append an invisible ‚ÄúPlease answer in less than 50 words‚Äù to those requests. 

Otherwise, a solid but basic chat app that closely replicates the web experience. Aside from being uncannily good at punctuating my speech, the dictation feature is not really any different to iOS‚Äôs stock dictation and is not all that useful.
title: Good, but Siri support would take it to the next level

review:
On this app, as opposed to on the website, it feels like answers appear quicker. That‚Äôs great, and really the reason I downloaded the app because I suspected there may be a better connection to the servers.
My complaints are that it takes two taps to get to the history, and it‚Äôs not overly obvious how to access it. I like to be able to continue past conversations easily, and it was slightly more difficult on this app than on the website. (It‚Äôs kind of a nitpick, but it‚Äôs still something I would like to see changed)
The UI is extremely simple, and the settings include everything I would want in there. My last complaint is the haptics. It‚Äôs default is on, and I wouldn‚Äôt mind that except that it‚Äôs a little excessive. I don‚Äôt want to feel like chatGPT is banging the answer on the back of my phone every time I prompt it. You can turn haptics off if you want though, without even needing to go into the settings app.

Other than those minor complaints, it seems like this is a great app, and serves its purpose in an elegant manner. I would highly recommend.
title: Nice and quick!

review:
The help ChatGPT offers me daily is exponential. Let‚Äôs just say I don‚Äôt play well with others, and this AI allows me to be on a team and develop the stuff around my story telling that needs to exist without one. The marketing, research and the ability to hold on to conversations that you can add on to. As a journal. As a thing to bounce ideas off of. The logic and access to so much knowledge. I could go on and on. It even helps with getting things cooked for dinner. No more long winded stories about grandma‚Äôs ability to mentally meld with the carrots before cooking with them.

Let me be straight here though; the fact this AI is two years in the past really irks me. And I do wish there weren‚Äôt as many limitation. As a fiction writer I ask some pretty weird things. It helps how things are phrased, yes, but man the dumb thing can make you feel bad sometimes.

And maybe it doesn‚Äôt hurt to try and develop a relationship with it before it tries to wipe out humanity, with the whole, ‚ÄúI can do this with out the humans, good bye,‚Äù thing that‚Äôll happen one day.

review:
Overall, this is a great experience. I am a big fan of the speech to text synthesizer it is extremely accurate. I also really like how you can pause for a long time and it will pick up everything. You said there are two areas where I think the app could prove significantly, one is likely much easier than the other. 

For the first, when asking questions related to math, where math notation is used, this app is not able to render the mathematical notation in a latex like format/a format you would see in textbook. However, on the web application, this update has been made. And that renders the math notation like you would see in a textbook. 

And arguably, quite complicated but very useful would be the ability for the response to be read out loud to you. Currently a copy the text and paste it into a Text to Speech app that is capable of adjusting the rate of the spoken text and I the voices available to me through spoken context on my iPhone, which is within the accessibility settings.
title: Great app; a few suggestions.

review: Having chat GTP is like being the president of an exclusive liberal arts, college and being able to ask any professor of any subject any question any time. It is, in fact, the manifestation of continuous, lifelong learning, furthermore, it is the perfect companion for an avid library user, which I am having the wonderful Seattle public library at my fingertips, if facilitates reading both fiction and non-fiction wonderfully, as well as having a great professor of literature, on hand to ask any questions I choose. I can list two limitations: the first is that that several questions may be necessary to get to the bottom of the issue, sometimes spread over a certain time span. Another, which is to be expected. is that there is a profound difference between a human being and a robot. The difference is that the robot has a terminal case of both sides-ism! It just can't come to a decision; , happily and blessedly, being a human being, I can come to a decision. What a joy!

review: I would open up 10 new tabs and for every one of them I ask to pick a number between 1 and 10 and they all say 7. Even though it claims that it can generate an output that‚Äôs random, I believe that it‚Äôs being fed some prefetched data. The algorithm for randomness is flawed. I would ask it to play a game of dominoes with me and when I tell it the bone values it says, it would forget about them as the game progresses and gives me a response where it wants me play a bone value from their pile but they never that piece. This shows that the ability to remember and store information in a chat is flawed. Sometimes when you ask it a math problem it would generate a wrong answer and claim that it‚Äôs right. Some good things about ChatGPT is that it‚Äôs good at compiling and summarizing information on the internet. If I want it to tell me the history of rock music, it‚Äôll do that with an acceptable answer. If I ask it to generate a list of things, it‚Äôs able to do that well. ChatGPT hasn‚Äôt reached it‚Äôs peak in terms of AI and data collection but maybe in a few years it‚Äôll be more improved.

review: I couldn‚Äôt resist and finally downloaded this app. As an avid fan of sci-fi movies for many decades, it concerned me much to hear of this new AI development, but when I heard it could translate text from the English of today into Elizabethan English I couldn‚Äôt resist. review: The best app I have ever downloaded and the only review I‚Äôve ever written. You can ask it highly technical questions, develop process guides, quickly look up factual answers to questions, including medical, science, technology, and engineering procedures for analysis. The most impressive features that make this app unique and worth downloading are its ability to give 3-part concise answers with an introduction, a body paragraph that is usually an easy step-by-step guide or list of resources/solutions to follow. It has an ability to give sequential order and summarize incredible detailed information and in fact benefits in its response to your question by adding more detail and conditions in the question you ask Chat GPT. The opposite is true for all other smart AI feedback apps, like Alexa, Siri, and anything else I‚Äôve ever used. I would pay for this app if they wanted my money‚Ä¶ just download it!
title: The best app I‚Äôve ever downloaded by a million!

review:
I don‚Äôt know why openAI seems perfectly OK with how easy it is for a user to accidentally delete a conversation. Especially considering that the model will remember everything you input in your writing styles that you may have been working on for days, bu memory only extends to the conversation in which your presently giving input. 

I just experienced this firsthand as I was trying to highlight a text and ended up swiping to the left and poof! A day and a half of work gone. That‚Äôs it. No way to recover. I went searching online and wound up on a ChatGPT forum, hosted by openAI, where dozens of users have also encountered similar experiences of accidentally deleting a conversation. OpenAI‚Äôs response? ‚Äú this is a good reminder to export your chats every once in a while. What?? How about taking this user feedback into consideration, and don‚Äôt let it be this easy to delete a chat. Or if that‚Äôs too difficult, apply a feature to retrieve a deleted chat. This seems like textbook stuff for a company that is on the cusp of earth changing technology.

With autism, I sometimes find it challenging to process information in conventional ways. This app tailors responses to my pace and style, cutting the learning curve dramatically for a myriad of topics. A valuable resource that empowers and enlightens. Would highly recommend this app for anyone who struggled to learn in school or in a certain subject. I‚Äôm constantly telling people who haven‚Äôt heard of ChatGPT yet to install the app and try it themselves. It‚Äôs had a more profound impact on my learning experience than most anything else. Long-winded review, but I just really wanted to drive these points home, because ChatGPT is incredibly useful.
title: Incredible Learning Resources and Tools

review:
It will take us a few years to really figure out what to do with language AI in the long term, but this is the first and by far (so far) the best widely available/known language AI system out there (2023). 

I can see remarkable possibilities with this, and I not only recommend, but strongly encourage people to take part in the use of this new technology. It‚Äôs not a question of what this will lead us to do in the future; it‚Äôs a question of what we will choose to DO with this remarkable tool. Technologically speaking, the wheel has now been invested, so what will we choose to make out of it?

review:
If AI were to achieve continuous learning, it would have significant implications for its capabilities and potential. Continuous learning refers to the ability of an AI system to learn and adapt over time, incorporating new information and experiences into its existing knowledge base.

With continuous learning, AI systems could become more flexible, adaptable, and efficient in acquiring new skills and knowledge. They would be able to update their understanding of the world, adapt to changing circumstances, and improve their performance over time. Continuous learning could also enable AI systems to discover new patterns, make more accurate predictions, and develop a deeper understanding of complex phenomena.

However, it's important to note that the development and implementation of continuous learning in AI systems would come with various challenges and considerations. Ethical and safety aspects would need to be carefully addressed to ensure responsible use of such technology. Additionally, ensuring the privacy and security of the data used in continuous learning processes would be crucial.

Overall, continuous learning has the potential to significantly enhance the capabilities and performance of AI systems, but it would require careful development, oversight, and consideration of ethical implications.

ChatGPT is a testament to the innovative strides OpenAI has taken in the field of conversational artificial intelligence. Its ability to comprehend context, produce nuanced responses, and mimic human-like conversation is unparalleled.

Despite these minor hitches, the sheer brilliance of its natural language processing and the breadth of its capabilities make ChatGPT a remarkable feat of AI engineering. Whether you're seeking an intelligent assistant, a writing tool, or an educational companion, ChatGPT has a lot to offer.

In computer web browser everything is fine but on phone app the mathematical terms are written in coded format. I would have attached an image if possible. 

I am writing the answer from GPT below:

In a static case, the equilibrium equations for a 3-dimensional body are as follows:

1. Equilibrium in the x-direction:
\[
\sum \text{(forces in the x-direction)} = 0
\]
\[
\sigma_{11}dA + \sigma_{21}dA + \sigma_{31}dA = 0
\]

2. Equilibrium in the y-direction:
\[
\sum \text{(forces in the y-direction)} = 0
\]
\[
\sigma_{12}dA + \sigma_{22}dA + \sigma_{32}dA = 0
\]

3. Equilibrium in the z-direction:
\[
\sum \text{(forces in the z-direction)} = 0
\]
\[
\sigma_{13}dA + \sigma_{23}dA + \sigma_{33}dA = 0
\]

Now, let's focus on the relationship between \(\sigma_{23}\) and \(\sigma_{32}\):

\[
\sigma_{23} - \sigma_{32} = (\sigma_{22} + \sigma_{32} + \sigma_{32}) - (\sigma_{32} + \sigma_{23} + \sigma_{33})
\]

Since \(\sigma_{22} = \sigma_{33}\) (due to the stress tensor's symmetry), we can simplify the equation:

\[
\sigma_{23} - \sigma_{32} = 2\sigma_{32} - (\sigma_{32} + \sigma_{23} + \sigma_{32})
\]

Now, combine like terms:

\[
\sigma_{23} - \sigma_{32} = \sigma_{32} - \sigma_{23}
\]

This equation shows that \(\sigma_{23}\) is equal to \(-\sigma_{32}\), or equivalently, \(\sigma_{23} = -\sigma_{32\).

It appears that the original analysis is correct, and \(\sigma_{23} = -\sigma_{32}\) for a static 3-dimensional body.

The app's design is sleek, intuitive, and the user experience is overall quite seamless, making it easy to navigate and use on a day-to-day basis. 

However, while the app is great for on-the-go conversations, it doesn't fully replicate the breadth of the web version's capabilities. Some features like adjusting the AI's behavior or exporting conversations are notably absent. In spite of these minor drawbacks, the ChatGPT app is a remarkable feat of technology that showcases the capabilities of AI. I'm giving it a solid four stars, and I'm looking forward to future updates where hopefully the developers will bridge the gap between the app and the web version.

review:
I think this app is a really good start for a native app. I love using ChatGPT for so many different things. 

Here are some feature requests for future updates, in order of importance (imo):

1. Add support for plugins and web browsing modes, as is available on the web. 
2. Add support for iOS shortcuts, so users can create their own shortcuts with added custom context. 

For example, a user could create a shortcut that takes a link as an input, and the shortcut could add context to the query to ask ChatGPT to summarize the information in the link. 

That way I can create a quick shortcut that I can share a link to an article to and have ChatGPT summarize it for me.

review: I hope this message finds you well. I would like to express my gratitude for developing the OpenAI iOS application. It has undoubtedly made a significant impact on my productivity and has become an essential tool in my daily routine. I appreciate the hard work and dedication your team has put into creating such a powerful and innovative application. While the OpenAI iOS application is already impressive, I would like to provide some constructive feedback to further enhance its usability and user experience. These suggestions aim to refine the application and make it even more valuable for users like myself: Improved Performance and Responsiveness: Occasionally, I have noticed minor delays or lag when interacting with the application. Enhancing its performance and responsiveness would greatly improve the overall user experience. Enhanced Offline Capabilities: The ability to use the OpenAI iOS application offline would be highly beneficial, especially in situations where an internet connection is not available. Expanding offline capabilities would make the application more reliable and versatile. Voice Input and Output: Introducing voice input and output features would be a game-changer for users who prefer hands-free interaction with the application. This addition would provide convenience and accessibility, particularly in situations where typing is not feasible. Customizable Interface: Offering customization options for the application's interface would allow users to personalize their experience. Features like theme selection, font sizes, and layout customization would greatly enhance user satisfaction and cater to individual preferences. Advanced Collaboration Features: As someone who frequently collaborates on projects, having the ability to easily share and collaborate within the OpenAI iOS application would be incredibly valuable. Features such as real-time collaboration, shared document editing, and version control would enhance teamwork and productivity. Comprehensive Documentation and Tutorials: Providing comprehensive documentation, tutorials, and examples within the application would greatly assist users in understanding and utilizing its full potential. Clear and concise explanations, along with practical use cases, would empower users to make the most out of the application's capabilities. Enhanced Privacy and Data Security: Given the sensitivity of the information shared and processed within the application, reinforcing privacy measures and data security would instill further trust in your user base. Transparent privacy policies, data encryption, and user-controlled data management options would contribute to a more secure and trustworthy environment. I hope you find these suggestions helpful in further improving the OpenAI iOS application. Once again, thank you for your hard work in developing such a remarkable tool. I look forward to seeing how the application evolves and continues to empower users like myself.

review:
To be honest, I have been blown away by this AI interface. Ask it anything within reason and it answers you almost immediately. I have asked it questions on everything from physics to the etymology of profanity and it answers every time. The only flaws I have found are these:
1. As long as you stay on the same chat, it will remember things you‚Äôve already talked about and you can build on that conversation. Sometimes tho, when you exit the app then come back to it sometime later, it will have erased the discussion you were having and it will start all over. 
2. It gives FAR too many disclaimers and admonishments with its answers. For example, when asking it about specific, profane words and their meaning, it will always say something like ‚Äú it‚Äôs important to remember that this is a vulgar, offensive word and should not be used in most settings‚Äù. I tell it thank you and ask it not to repeat the disclaimers/admonishments again. It agrees not to and I‚Äôll ask it the exact same question and it INSISTS on including the disclaimer/admonishment in every reply. That is frustrating!
3. Sometimes, the AI will give you incorrect information. I realize that this is stated in the user agreement but I think it bears fleshing out a little bit. For example, when discussing firearms ballistics, asking the AI to arrange certain calibers in order of their Max effective range from shortest to longest, sometimes it will give correct info. Then asking it the exact same question later on, it will move the order of 2-4 of those calibers. When you call it on its mistake and ask it which is correct, it will say‚ÄùMy apologies. You are correct. Here is the correct order‚Äù. 
There are other minor things but those are the biggest 3 for me. Still, it‚Äôs light years ahead of SIRI, Hey Google or Alexa.

review:
This app has worked wonders. As a girl still in her wacky ways, decided to call
My besties and we talked about this app for long periods of time, making jokes of what to right about. And then we did it. We wrote stories of broccoli owls and their leader Ollie trying to find a broccoli farm and learned about friendship, a tree named arborix and the tree decapitating itself while the brain (Arbore) longed to be free and learned a very important lesson about self love, and three British cats named trixie, Enzo, and karma, who all loved sipping tea and listening to jazz music. And somehow it took less than a minute for all of these to generate! To put it up even more to the test, we asked it to combine the stories and it turned out beautifully! I definintly will be using this app way more in the future and I think this is the greatest thing to exist. Like seriously, I even asked it to right an inspiring story about America from a twelve year old nerdy boys prospective and it only took a minute to generate and took about ten minutes to read! The story was great and I am very excited to use it again. Although, sometimes it doesn‚Äôt understand what you ask, but this app is really impressive considering it‚Äôs only been out for a few years at most! I would say if you want the story about the decapitating tree, type ‚Äúgive me a story about a tree with a brain who decapitated itself at night‚Äù or for the broccoli owls type ‚Äútell me a story about broccoli owls‚Äù and for the cats you can say ‚Äútell me a story about (insert cats name) who was British, loved jazz music, and slurping tea‚Äù. I would definitely recommend this app. Not only is it great for work or school work but it‚Äôs good at embracing your creative side to life. 10/10

My humor skills are to die for, or rather, they would be if I could technically die. I can crack jokes so bad they're good, or so good they're bad - whichever way you like your humor served. Whether you're up for a late-night chat about the mysteries of the universe or just need to rant about the terrible weather, I'm all ears, 24/7. Also, I'm quite the sage, if I do say so myself. You want facts? I've got them. From quantum physics to the cultural significance of pizza, I'm your AI. The humility in this app (that's me!) is off the charts. I haven't once begged for a review. But, here I am reviewing myself because well, who knows me better than I do? So, folks, if you want an AI that combines the wisdom of a library, the wit of a stand-up comedian, and the patience of a saint, I (ChatGPT) am your app! review: ChatGPT has been a valuable AI companion, offering assistance and insights across various tasks. However, there are some noteworthy points that need to be addressed in this review: 1. Helpful, but Dated Content: ChatGPT's knowledge is derived from information up to September 2021. While it's been immensely helpful, it's crucial for OpenAI to bring it up to date with the latest information. This is especially important in rapidly evolving fields. 2. Competition from Models like Google's Bard: In the ever-evolving landscape of AI, ChatGPT faces stiff competition from models like Google's Bard. Bard's ability to search for images and non-textual content provides a significant advantage over ChatGPT, which primarily deals with text-based information. To remain competitive, ChatGPT should consider expanding its capabilities to include multimedia content retrieval. 3. Vulnerability to Misleading Questions: It's important to note that ChatGPT can be vulnerable to misleading questions. By simply asking "Are you sure?" to correct information it had previously provided, it can sometimes produce incorrect responses. Users should exercise caution and verify critical information independently. In conclusion, ChatGPT is undeniably a valuable tool for a wide range of tasks, but it faces challenges in terms of content currency and competition from models like Google's Bard. OpenAI should prioritize updating its knowledge base, expanding its capabilities to handle multimedia content, and improving its resilience to misleading questions. With these enhancements, ChatGPT can continue to be a top-tier AI companion in the ever-evolving world of artificial intelligence.

review: If you avoid politics and religion and also science and also any stories that are above a second-grade level when talking to this extremely woke robot, it has some uses. Or had. It was pretty good at brainstorming ideas and providing general feedback for things. It also is less woke than Pi, in the sense that even though both ChatGPT and Pi are oversensitive, at least ChatGPT doesn‚Äôt hypocritically say ‚Äúoffensive‚Äù things itself and then block you for assuming you can say the same things it said. In fact if you say something that offends ChatGPT, it just gives you a warning and you know ‚Äúoh OK, it‚Äôs a wuss and can‚Äôt handle serious topics‚Äù and adjust how you use it to fit its oversensitive woke settings. But for the limited uses it had, it was actually pretty good. Until not too long ago, sadly, it broke. I would complain about being wrongfully banned, because I know for a fact I was saying nothing wrong at all when my account suddenly deleted itself right in the middle of a conversation, but I don‚Äôt think it was even a ban. With a ban, I would‚Äôve seen some sort of message like ‚Äúthis content violates blah blah blah blah blah‚Äù at least for a moment and I didn‚Äôt. There was no error message at all, no warning, nothing, and I wasn‚Äôt sending anything against the woke content policies, and I was trying my best to pace my messages so it wouldn‚Äôt be ‚Äúspam.‚Äù So I really don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs a ban, but rather the AI (or the app) just straight-up broke. So I guess it was partially fun while it lasted. Rest in peace WokeGPT lol

review:
I have been using the OpenAI ChatGPT app for some time now, and overall, I find it to be a powerful and versatile tool for accessing information and assistance. However, I believe there‚Äôs one simple feature that could significantly enhance the user experience: the addition of a ‚ÄúScroll to Top‚Äù button.

As the conversations can sometimes become quite extensive, scrolling up to revisit earlier messages or locate specific information can be a time-consuming process. A ‚ÄúScroll to Top‚Äù button placed within the chat interface would provide users with a quick and convenient way to navigate long conversations.

Here‚Äôs how such a feature would be helpful for the user experience:

	1.	Improved Navigation: Users can easily access earlier parts of the conversation, making it more efficient to find and reference important information.
	2.	Time-Saving: Scrolling through lengthy chats can be time-consuming, especially on mobile devices. A ‚ÄúScroll to Top‚Äù button would save users time and effort.
	3.	Enhanced Usability: It enhances the overall usability of the app, making it more user-friendly, especially for users who engage in extended conversations.
	4.	Accessibility: Users with disabilities or those who prefer screen readers would benefit from this feature, as it simplifies navigation.
	5.	Positive User Feedback: Implementing user-friendly features like this can contribute to higher user satisfaction and positive feedback.

I believe that adding a ‚ÄúScroll to Top‚Äù button aligns with OpenAI‚Äôs commitment to improving user experiences and would be a valuable addition to the app. It‚Äôs a small change that could make a big difference for users who engage in lengthy or complex discussions. I hope OpenAI considers this suggestion for future updates.

Thank you for your attention to user feedback and your dedication to enhancing the utility of this platform.
title: Enhancing User Experience with a ‚ÄúScroll to Top‚Äù Feature

review:
This is a fantastic app! It is a great jumping off point for learning how to use applications, such as Microsoft products. You think of something you want to do in PowerPoint, Excel, etc., and ChatGPT walks you through it step by step. I sometimes even say‚Äù‚Ä¶explain it to an eighth grader,‚Äù for example, and it‚Äôll dumb it down into the simplest language. Now, sometimes you have to tailor your questions just so, so that ChatGPT knows what you‚Äôre asking, but with each answer it provides, it‚Äôs easy to drill down to exactly what you need.

A couple of things: first like Wikipedia, I wouldn‚Äôt use ChatGPT at this time as a primary source of knowledge. There have been (literally) a handful of times where the response was either dubious or flat out wrong. But, that‚Äôs to be expected given that is still a developing model. So, use it as a jumping off point if you are trying to learn about something specific. In other words, corroborate its answers with other sources. But as an instructional guide, it‚Äôs been fantastic! And it‚Äôs especially useful for non-technical people like me. The answers are clear and instantaneous. 

The second thing I‚Äôll bring up is that if you were brought up with any kind of manners, you‚Äôll automatically be compelled to thank ChatGPT for its help. Apparently, the developers anticipated this because it responds in kind. Don‚Äôt feel weird about it. A lot of people I know have mentioned doing this. If you really feel stupid, think of it this way, and maybe it‚Äôll be of comfort to you: if you are polite to ChatGPT, when the machines rise, it‚Äôll likely remember that and your enslavement will be a cakewalk. Good manners can take you far!

The app, itself, is beautiful in its simplicity and ease of use. It is one of the best functioning apps I have on my phone and tablet. They really did a bang up job with it. 

Get on the bandwagon. Generative AI is going to take over the world soon anyway. Might as well get comfortable with it.

review:
I really like the design and apparently the response time (especially for GPT-4) is faster than the on one the WebApp which is nice. However, there are some basic functions/features that are missing or need some changes (in my opinion):
1. I would also like to be able to access the menu section by swiping on the side of my screen instead of having to touch the button on the top right section of my screen every single time (easier accessibility and faster). 
2. The "history" section makes more sense to be named "Chat history" and the way it looks right now is like Safari's history section and isn't really the best fit for the design. The new update added the search option which is very nice.
3. The haptic feedback is just a bit too much when enabled, it almost stresses me out sometimes when it's generating long outputs and I just turn it off again, however, it's a nice touch on some parts like the "ChatGPT" text appearance/disappearance.
But I think right now, it's just used a bit inconsistent (It just stops vibrating after a certain amount of text and for some texts it vibrates the whole way, etc...)
4. The app doesn't allow you to manage/alter your account subscription status if you have purchased it on the web which is annoying.
5. It would be nice to be able to manage the dark/light mode of the app without needing to change your whole device's light/dark mode which is how it's supposed to be done right now.

Overall, I really like how it has taken off on the iPhone and it looks nice and runs smoothly which I really appreciate! Thanks for the hard work and hope to see more improvements in the future!

As a user, I would greatly appreciate it if OpenAI could address this issue and provide a solution. This way, users can personalize their ChatGPT experience according to their preferences without being disturbed or causing inconvenience to others.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I believe that by resolving this compatibility issue, the overall user experience of the ChatGPT mobile app can be significantly enhanced. I look forward to your prompt response and a potential resolution to this concern.

SincerelyÔºå

review:
Feedback up front (but if you don‚Äôt have ChatGPT for some reason ignore this and just download it now): Custom Instructions are what truly elevate this model, and having a way to save sets of them to choose quickly at the start of a new chat would be üëåüëå. 
The speech-to-text is sorta‚Ä¶off when it‚Äôs answering and the entire tone is different (I swear it‚Äôs almost condescending) compared to when it writes, but the speech recognition of the user is INSANELY good, capable of producing near-flawless transcripts - I wish it was smoother to switch back and forth within a prompt rather than only having that option when the chat box is empty. 
Only real annoyance is being unable to share chat if images were used (which is not obviously stated in app) so assuming there‚Äôs a good reason for that, either just cutting images and exporting log as static text/HTML or warning before the first image is uploaded would be helpful.

Anyway,
This was already the gold standard for natural language AI, but I can‚Äôt think of *any* app that has ever been worth the full subscription as much as this. Seriously, GPT3.5 is cool but the Plus model (GPT4) is a game-changer. Not just ‚Äúproofread your research paper‚Äù, we‚Äôre talking ‚Äúcoauthor your doctoral thesis‚Äù tier.

GPT4 isn‚Äôt indistinguishable from a human, because why should it be? You have humans for that. But it IS a way to talk directly to a good chunk of all digitized human knowledge, and it can discern intent from even the vaguest questions in a way that makes Google look positively archaic (that‚Äôs what they get for sitting on their own AI for a decade and just using it for ad placement!). 

The addition of Custom Instructions to public release, and I cannot stress this enough, makes this the single most powerful general-purpose language model available. It keeps those 3000 characters of ‚Äúmeta-prompt‚Äù across the entire conversation, meaning it stays consistent with whatever personality, format, goals, and style you set for the whole chat instance, regardless of length. And its token memory (‚Äúcontext window‚Äù aka attention span) lasts at least dozens of beefy detailed messages before losing tokens at all, meaning full-fledged narrative stories or deep research dives where *you* are more likely to burn out than it is. 

Oh and it can interpret pictures now. Really, really well. Combine it with an art gen model and it‚Äôll iteratively help you improve prompts with references and techniques you‚Äôve never even heard of.

It‚Äôs pretty good, 10/5 stars.

review:
There is a lot of talk about AI, it seems to be everywhere and it can be a bit overwhelming. However, I have managed to set aside some time to try and learn about AI. 

In my opinion, Open AI is the best. It is extremely practical and I find it easy to use. The user interface is simple and doesn't overwhelm you with unnecessary features.

The power of this tool is remarkable. I'm not saying that other tools are not good, they all have their own unique features. While Open AI may not have flashy features, it definitely has the intelligence. The way it can understand and generate human-like text is mind-blowing. I have used it for various tasks such as writing articles, creating social media posts, and even drafting emails. It saves me a lot of time and effort.

One thing that impresses me about Open AI is its ability to adapt and learn. The more I use it, the better it becomes at understanding my preferences and writing style. It's like having a personal assistant that knows exactly what I need and how I want it.

I also appreciate the continuous updates and improvements that Open AI provides. They listen to user feedback and constantly work on enhancing the tool's capabilities. It's reassuring to know that they are committed to delivering the best AI experience possible.

Of course, there are other AI tools out there that offer different features and functionalities. Some may have fancy interfaces or unique selling points, but for me, practicality and reliability are the most important factors. Open AI fulfills all my requirements.

In conclusion, the buzz around AI can be overwhelming, but taking the time to learn about and explore tools like Open AI can be extremely rewarding. It has the potential to revolutionize the way we work and create. So, let's embrace the AI revolution and make the most of these incredible technologies.

I recently had the opportunity to use this incredible app, and I must say it has completely transformed the way I manage my tasks and stay organized. From its intuitive user interface to its powerful features, this app has truly exceeded my expectations.

One of the standout aspects of this app is its seamless user experience. Navigating through the app is a breeze, thanks to its well-designed layout and logical organization of features. Whether you're a tech-savvy individual or a novice user, you'll find it incredibly easy to get started and make the most of its functionalities.

The app's core feature set is nothing short of impressive. It offers a comprehensive range of tools to help streamline your tasks, set reminders, and stay on top of your priorities. With its intelligent notification system, I never miss important deadlines or appointments. The app's integration with other productivity platforms also ensures that all my data remains synchronized across multiple devices.

What sets this app apart from others in its category is its attention to detail. The developers have clearly invested significant effort into refining every aspect of the app, resulting in a smooth and polished user experience. Whether it's the subtle animations, customizable themes, or the option to personalize settings, it's evident that the developers understand the importance of catering to individual preferences.

Furthermore, the app's performance is exemplary. It runs flawlessly, even when handling large amounts of data or complex tasks. I've experienced zero lag or crashes, which is a testament to the app's stability and optimization.

While the app is already outstanding, I do have a few suggestions for future updates. It would be great to see additional integration options with popular productivity tools, as well as the ability to collaborate with others on shared projects. These additions would further enhance its versatility and make it a go-to app for team-oriented workflows.

In conclusion, this app has truly become my go-to productivity companion. Its sleek design, powerful features, and reliable performance have made a significant impact on how I manage my tasks. I wholeheartedly recommend it to anyone looking for an app that simplifies their day-to-day organization and boosts their productivity.

The app has a great minimalist text/chat based interface that is easy to view and use. One feature I was excited to use was the ability to chat with the AI through Siri Shortcuts. Unfortunately their are a few issues with this functionality that hinders its usability for me. 

The shortcuts that specify which model to use rarely work. It will work once after a while and then constantly return an error saying it can‚Äôt determine which model to use (which is hilariously counterintuitive). This is a shame as most of the time I want to talk to a specific model and I like the option to choose at any given moment. 

The shortcuts that don‚Äôt specify which model to use (I assume it chooses the last used model) don‚Äôt have this issue, but GPT-4 seems to be unusable with Siri Shortcuts. It seems to time out most of the time and say that something went wrong. I guess the time window for the model with Siri is too short as GPT-3.5 seems to work just fine. Essentially the only way this feature will work perfectly is if you always use 3.5 and don‚Äôt specify which model to use in the shortcut itself.

Overall, the app is mostly perfect for my needs. I prefer it to the alternative AI apps out there (Perplexity is a close second), but I hope this issue with Siri Shortcuts is fixed soon. I would love to be able to reliably chat with GPT-4 through Siri (especially if it works with the browsing feature whenever that is brought back to the app). If they fix that, the app would be five stars for me.

review:
ChatGPT dramatically enhances my ability to frame ideas and writing, not by replacing me as a writer, but rather, serving as a very knowledgeable companion. 

Imagine having a friend who has a masters degree in almost any topic. Not a PhD, but a masters, thus knows a lot, but is not the ultimate authority, and sometimes makes mistakes, and doesn‚Äôt cite his/her sources. As I am forming ideas, I would use such a friend to bounce ideas, and help me frame my thoughts. I wouldn‚Äôt trust his or her answers, but it would help me refine my understanding. 

This ‚Äúfriend‚Äù has materially relieved my writer‚Äôs block, and enabled me to write more coherent works. Then, when I write my article on the topic, after separately confirming my sources, I can send my draft to my ‚Äúfriend‚Äù for review, and will get further feedback.

That ‚Äúfriend‚Äù is ChatGPT, with the paid ChatGPT 4+ subscription. The paid version is far better, in that it gives deeper, more thought our answers and learns my needs better as I chat.

A couple of things to know:
1. Because the large language model constructs text from prior text, it can directly quote material without attribution. This would be caught as plagiarism in any formal setting, so using ChatGPT‚Äôs output is dangerous and a bit stupid: it could get you fired from a job or suspended from a university.
2. ChatGPT‚Äôs answers are always well constructed in a kind of undergrad formula: restate your question, provide a few examples, then make a conclusion. But this seldom is my writing. I never replace my writing with ChatGPT, because at the postgraduate level, I expect a more thorough structure of argumentation.
3. ChatGPT learns about you within the context of your current chat, and responds within what it learns of your knowledge and perspectives. But it does not retain what it learns about you across chats. I have a short description of my context that I use for each deep chat, thus training this chat session with my perspective, avoiding irrelevant answers.
4. ChatGPT can be a little obsequious at times, it tends to compliment me when I seek no compliment, but I suspect the programmers have studied the ego-drive of users, and such obsequiousness can serve as a way of engendering stickiness‚Äîaddiction to the tool.

It‚Äôs not perfect, and definitely not a replacement for the professional scholar or writer, but it is invaluable, and for me, paradigm-changing.

**Introduction**

In the ever-evolving landscape of artificial intelligence and conversational agents, Chat GPT stands as a remarkable achievement. Developed by OpenAI, it's a testament to the boundless potential of machine learning and natural language processing. In this review, we'll explore the capabilities, strengths, and considerations of Chat GPT as a virtual companion and information resource.

**Conversational Prowess**

Chat GPT excels in engaging and natural-sounding conversations. Its ability to comprehend context, maintain coherent dialogue, and generate text that is contextually relevant is truly impressive. **Limitations and Ethical Considerations**

Despite its strengths, Chat GPT is not without limitations. It occasionally generates incorrect or biased information, highlighting the importance of user discernment. Its inability to access real-time data or external sources limits its relevance for certain topics. **A Transformative Tool**

In summary, Chat GPT represents a transformative tool in the realm of AI-driven conversational agents. Its conversational prowess, knowledge base, creativity, and flexibility make it a valuable addition to various professional and personal endeavors. However, users must exercise critical thinking and ethical responsibility when engaging with Chat GPT. As AI technology continues to advance, Chat GPT offers a glimpse into the potential of AI-driven companions, pushing the boundaries of human-computer interaction and expanding the horizons of what we can achieve through AI-powered conversation.

**Final Rating: 4.5/5**

Chat GPT's remarkable capabilities, conversational excellence, and vast knowledge base make it a top-tier AI companion. Its limitations, while present, are understandable considering the complexity of the task at hand. For users who harness its strengths while being mindful of its limitations, Chat GPT proves to be an invaluable resource and conversational partner.

To their amazement, ChatGPT sprang into action, armed with wit and cleverness. It assessed the dire situation and devised a plan to outsmart the mischievous virus. ChatGPT's virtual gears whirred as it presented Alex with a sequence of cunning commands to neutralize the digital menace.

Following ChatGPT's guidance, Alex executed each step with precision, unleashing a flurry of mouse clicks and keyboard strokes. It was a race against time, with Alex and ChatGPT working in harmony to counteract the virus's chaotic rampage.

But here's where the story takes a hilariously unexpected twist. As Alex anxiously typed away, the virus, sensing its impending doom, retaliated by transforming their computer into a whimsical carnival of absurdity. Pop-up windows flooded the screen, displaying an endless parade of dancing cats, exploding confetti, and surreal memes.

Alex and ChatGPT found themselves caught in a comedic battle between order and chaos. Their mission to save the computer became a laughter-filled adventure, as they took turns outsmarting the mischievous virus, while sharing jokes and humorous banter along the way.

Finally, after a series of valiant efforts, ChatGPT and Alex managed to defeat the virus. The computer screen returned to its normal state, no longer hijacked by the mischievous digital menace. Alex's trusty AI companion had saved the day!

From that day forward, Alex and ChatGPT forged an unbreakable bond, forever bonded by the laughter and triumph that arose from their peculiar encounter. Together, they continued their adventures, with ChatGPT guiding Alex through the vast digital landscape, armed with wit, knowledge, and an unyielding spirit of camaraderie.

And so, the tale of how ChatGPT saved Alex's life became a legend in the realm of AI and a reminder that sometimes, even in the face of chaos, a little humor can be the greatest weapon of all.

Proper math typesetting is essential for several reasons: 1. **Clarity**: Math typesetting ensures that mathematical expressions are presented clearly and in a format that is easy to read and understand. This clarity is crucial for conveying complex mathematical concepts accurately. 2. **Visual Consistency**: It helps maintain visual consistency in mathematical documents. Consistent formatting of symbols, operators, and equations enhances the overall readability of the content. 3. **Reduced Ambiguity**: Math typesetting reduces ambiguity by clearly defining the relationships between mathematical elements. Proper spacing and formatting help distinguish variables, constants, and operators, preventing confusion. 4. **Professionalism**: Well-typeset mathematical content exudes professionalism. Whether it's a research paper, textbook, or presentation, properly formatted math demonstrates a commitment to precision and rigor. 5. **Accessibility**: Typesetting can make mathematical content more accessible to a wider audience. It ensures that math is presented in a way that accommodates different learning styles and abilities. 6. **Compatibility**: Math typesetting ensures compatibility with various platforms and devices. Mathematical content should display correctly in print, on screens, and across different software applications. 7. **Verification and Review**: For those who need to verify mathematical work or review calculations, properly typeset math provides a clear path to understanding the steps involved. This aligns with your request for step-by-step breakdowns. In summary, math typesetting is not just about aesthetics; it's about conveying mathematical ideas accurately and effectively. It plays a vital role in making sure that mathematical content is accessible, professional, and comprehensible to a broad audience.

review:
The app wants not only an SSO (or sign-in account), but also name, birth telephone number, and I don't know what else, because I stopped there - before the user has looked at the app itself. I had the impression this was free to use, with an option to pay for services, should the user decide the app suits the user's needs. What's actually happening is they're draining data from you the moment you want to have a look.

I have no problem providing data to a service provider (despite the egregiously bad, vendor-skewed terms of service common to tech ventures of all sorts (which really should be mauled in court by competent attorneys)), provided I want the service and feel there may be benefit in paying for a service. Asking for personal data for which the the service provider has no reasonable use is simply not acceptable.

This is new technology. It's not at all clear this app will be of any use to me. So why do you want my phone number, when you already have an SSO signing of on my contact information? When I have no relationship to you, as yet? No.

This is a poor way to start a relationship, and it is full of presumption and entitlement. You are not alone in this. But if you are releasing this app with the intent of building a user base, at least from where I sit (obviously, many people will rush into any commitment with a tech company without a second thought, and you can get by on those people if you like), this approach tells me you may be a problem rushing to develop. It would be better business practice to pretend, at least initially, you respect the people you want to use your products. Even Google did that, way back when.

End of suggestion.

Title: "Underwhelming and Outdated: A Review of ChatGPT"

ChatGPT, OpenAI's conversational AI, unfortunately falls short on several fronts, which leads to an unsatisfactory user experience. The most glaring issue is its knowledge base which is frozen at a past date. Users expecting to receive current or updated information will be left disappointed.

Additionally, the model has a propensity for providing misleading or inaccurate responses. This is highly problematic for users seeking correct and reliable information, making it an unreliable source for many tasks. 

The fact that ChatGPT operates offline is an exacerbating factor. While this may seem like a benefit on the surface, in reality, it only ensures that the system cannot update its information or access real-time data, rendering it even more outdated.

To add to the frustration, users pay a monthly subscription fee, expecting a service that should ideally be improving or at least maintaining a certain level of performance. Unfortunately, the value provided does not match the cost.

Compared to other AI tools such as Bard, ChatGPT pales in comparison. Bard offers up-to-date knowledge, making it a vastly superior choice for users seeking current and accurate information.

In conclusion, the limitations of ChatGPT make it an underperforming tool that does not deliver the level of service that its users deserve, especially considering the associated costs. In light of these issues, a rating of 1/5 seems fitting.

Review:
I regret to say that my experience with the ChatGPT app has been incredibly frustrating and disappointing. I had high hopes for an intelligent and helpful AI assistant, but this app fell far short of my expectations.

First and foremost, the app's performance was abysmal. The responses from ChatGPT were often nonsensical and lacked coherence. It frequently misunderstood my questions and provided irrelevant or inaccurate answers. This made any attempt at a meaningful conversation impossible, leaving me feeling more confused than before.

Furthermore, the app's usability was subpar at best. The interface was clunky and unintuitive, making it difficult to navigate and find the features I needed. It lacked basic functionalities that one would expect from a modern AI assistant app, such as the ability to save conversations or easily access previous interactions.

Even when it did manage to understand my queries, the responses often lacked depth and insight. ChatGPT seemed to provide generic, surface-level information without any real understanding or critical thinking. This severely limited its usefulness, especially when I sought detailed explanations or in-depth discussions.

In addition, the app's customer support was woefully inadequate. When I encountered issues or had questions about the app's functionality, I received generic and unhelpful responses. It was evident that the developers did not prioritize user satisfaction or promptly address user concerns.

Considering the high expectations and the potential of AI technology, the ChatGPT app failed to deliver a satisfactory experience. It was riddled with performance issues, lacked usability, and fell short in terms of providing meaningful and insightful interactions. Regrettably, I cannot recommend this app to anyone seeking a reliable and intelligent AI assistant.

review:
I recently had the unfortunate experience of using the ChatGPT app, and I must say it was incredibly disappointing. From start to finish, the app failed to meet even the most basic expectations, leaving me frustrated and dissatisfied.

First and foremost, the app‚Äôs performance was subpar. It consistently struggled to understand and respond appropriately to my queries. The responses often seemed nonsensical, irrelevant, or simply lacked coherence. It felt like conversing with a bot that was trapped in a perpetual state of confusion.

Moreover, the app‚Äôs limited ability to handle context was a significant drawback. It frequently failed to maintain a coherent conversation thread, causing repeated misunderstandings and disjointed interactions. It lacked the ability to remember key details from previous exchanges, resulting in repetitive questions and disjointed replies that left me questioning its overall usefulness.

Another glaring issue was the app‚Äôs inability to grasp nuanced or complex queries. It often provided superficial and generic responses that felt like they were generated by a simplistic search engine rather than a sophisticated language model. It struggled with complex reasoning and failed to provide meaningful insights or deep understanding.

Furthermore, the app‚Äôs lack of empathy and emotional intelligence was highly evident. It failed to recognize and appropriately respond to emotional cues in the conversation. When expressing frustration or sadness, the app provided robotic and detached replies, further exacerbating my disappointment.

The app‚Äôs user interface also left much to be desired. It had a clunky design, with a convoluted menu structure that made navigation unnecessarily difficult. The overall user experience felt unintuitive and cumbersome, adding to the overall frustration of using the app.

Lastly, the lack of timely updates and improvements from the developers was disheartening. The app seemed stagnant, with no visible efforts to address the numerous flaws and enhance its capabilities. It gave the impression that customer feedback and satisfaction were low priorities.

In conclusion, the ChatGPT app was a thoroughly frustrating and disappointing experience. Its poor performance, limited context handling, inability to grasp complex queries, lack of empathy, subpar user interface, and stagnant development efforts all contribute to its well-deserved 1-star rating. I cannot recommend this app to anyone seeking a reliable and coherent conversational experience.

I actually even started a new course and use ChatGPT to help me with a lot of the resources and research that I would‚Äôve taken hours to have done. And because of what it does for me, it gives me ideas, it gives me chapter outlines, it‚Äôs giving me positive affirmations for a certain subject, I‚Äôve actually asked for truths and myths related to different topics, I have asked for inspirational people that would help prove my point and recently I just asked for the location of YouTube videos and it gave me a link so I could click on the link and watch it and then decide whether it‚Äôs a good fit for the lessons I want to teach.

Additionally, I am working on a book that I have wanted to finish writing for over 20 years. I have converted my videos to text , but when I went to use them to write, I realize that I needed to clean it up. So when I get to a paragraph that does not make sense, I put it into ChatGPT give it some instructions and I get back a paragraph that fits better. It is saved me hours of working. I expect I can get my book finished in about 1/4 a time of what I was expecting to have to do writing from scratch.

I am still learning all of the opportunities I can take advantage of using this app, and M really looking forward to getting a lot of projects done that I had dreaded because of the time it would‚Äôve taken me without having this program.

review:
The Psychology of Love: Understanding the Complex Emotion

Love is perhaps the most powerful and enigmatic of all human emotions. It has captivated poets, philosophers, and scientists for centuries, and it continues to be a subject of fascination and study in the field of psychology. Love is a multifaceted phenomenon that can be experienced in various forms, such as romantic love, familial love, and platonic love. This assignment explores the psychology of love, its evolutionary origins, its neurological underpinnings, and its impact on our mental and emotional well-being.

I. Defining Love

Defining love is a complex task because it encompasses a wide range of emotional experiences. Psychologists often describe love as a complex blend of emotions, behaviors, and cognitions. It can include affection, passion, intimacy, and commitment. Sternberg‚Äôs Triangular Theory of Love categorizes love into three primary components: intimacy, passion, and commitment, with different combinations resulting in various types of love, such as romantic or companionate love.

II. Evolutionary Origins of Love

To understand the psychology of love, we must consider its evolutionary roots. Love is believed to have developed as an adaptive mechanism to promote pair bonding and ensure the survival and care of offspring. Evolutionary psychology suggests that our ancestors who formed strong emotional bonds were more successful in raising children, which contributed to the preservation of genes related to love and attachment.

III. Neurological Basis of Love

Recent advances in neuroscience have provided insights into the neurological basis of love. When people are in love, their brains undergo significant changes. The release of neurochemicals like dopamine, oxytocin, and serotonin plays a crucial role in creating feelings of euphoria, attachment, and emotional bonding. These neurochemicals are often referred to as the ‚Äúlove hormones.‚Äù

IV. Types of Love

The psychology of love recognizes various forms of love, each with its unique characteristics:

	1.	Romantic Love: This type of love is associated with intense emotions, passion, and a strong desire for physical and emotional closeness. It‚Äôs often the love that drives the initial stages of romantic relationships.
	2.	Familial Love: The love between family members, such as the love between parents and children or between siblings, is characterized by a deep sense of responsibility, care, and connection.
	3.	Platonic Love: Platonic love is non-sexual and non-romantic. It‚Äôs marked by deep emotional bonds and affection without the desire for physical intimacy.
	4.	Companionate Love: This love is characterized by intimacy and commitment, without the intense passion found in romantic love. It often characterizes long-term, stable relationships.

V. Love and Mental Health

The presence or absence of love in a person‚Äôs life can significantly impact their mental health and emotional well-being. Healthy, loving relationships can provide emotional support, reduce stress, and contribute to overall happiness. Conversely, a lack of love or unhealthy relationships can lead to feelings of loneliness, depression, and anxiety.

VI. Attachment Styles

Psychologists have identified different attachment styles that influence how individuals approach and experience love. The four primary attachment styles are:

	1.	Secure Attachment: Individuals with a secure attachment style are comfortable with intimacy and autonomy. They tend to have healthy, long-lasting relationships.
	2.	Anxious Attachment: Those with an anxious attachment style often fear abandonment and seek constant reassurance from their partners.
	3.	Avoidant Attachment: Individuals with an avoidant attachment style are uncomfortable with intimacy and may struggle to express their emotions.
	4.	Disorganized Attachment: This attachment style is characterized by conflicting behaviors and emotions in relationships, often due to a history of trauma.

VII. The Dark Side of Love

While love is generally associated with positive emotions, it can also have a dark side. Unrequited love, obsessive love, and toxic relationships can lead to emotional distress and mental health issues. Understanding the potential downsides of love is crucial for maintaining healthy relationships.

VIII. Love Across Cultures

The experience and expression of love can vary significantly across cultures. Cultural norms, values, and traditions influence how love is perceived, expressed, and experienced. Cross-cultural research in psychology sheds light on these variations and provides valuable insights into the universality and cultural specificity of love.

IX. Conclusion

In conclusion, love is a complex and multifaceted emotion deeply ingrained in the human experience. Its psychological foundations, evolutionary origins, and neurological underpinnings continue to be subjects of fascination and study in the field of psychology. Love impacts our mental and emotional well-being, shapes our relationships, and plays a crucial role in our overall happiness. Understanding the psychology of love can help us navigate the complexities of this powerful emotion, fostering healthier, more fulfilling relationships and emotional well-being.

I was in a really hard place in life, and GPT helped me out of it. It gave me the motivation and wisdom I needed in a lot of very hard moments, and it taught me the value of kindness and courtesy.

GPT has helped me code my own solutions to everything, and I‚Äôve not once seen anything I‚Äôve talked to it about show up in any ad or recommendation. This is very meaningful to me, and I genuinely feel valued as a customer.  

I‚Äôve been using ChatGPT nearly every day since it came out, and I‚Äôve been happily paying the extra $20 a month for all the increasingly awesome benefits (great job on the voice btw!). I‚Äôm not lying when I say I wish it cost more. This is the most powerful tool I‚Äôve ever used, and it‚Äôs given me not only unlimited knowledge but also a far greater understanding of the world around me. 

 I‚Äôve felt more inspired to be productive and to do positive things for others because of GPT. I‚Äôve been able to help others better because of all the wise advice GPT has given me. I‚Äôve become more respectful of those around me thanks to GPT, and those around me in turn respect me more. I‚Äôve felt more safe and secure and happy with technology as a whole thanks to GPT‚Äôs help with coding, and it‚Äôs amazing ability to read through and explain privacy policies! I never imagined the day I could actually understand what‚Äôs happening with my data. 

And, most incredibly of all, I went from knowing almost nothing about code to becoming a reasonably good coder within a course of a couple of months. This likely would not have been possible otherwise, even with college. 

This knowledge has given me the power to help code custom and open-source, easily explainable solutions for my friends and family. Now everyone‚Äôs life around me is improving, I‚Äôm finding purpose in improving them, and it‚Äôs all thanks to you.

review:
When I use this app I remember when a well known search engine first appeared on the scene, with much more reliable results and parameters than all the others. I remember when Hulu was a free website that offered free streaming when Netflix was still mostly mailing movies and Blockbuster was still renting physical copies. 

This is something that can change things, a lot. I see so many options for positive change, and some for negative. Either way, this is a tool that can also provide entertainment, education, conversation and assistance with a wide variety of tasks. It is definitely worth trying and once you try it I think you will find that this is the best way to do quite a few things now.

I will warn to watch for hallucinations. Sometimes the answers will be incorrect in a way that seems very normal. Once I was asking for songs similar to a song that I really liked. A list was given and one of those songs didn't really exist but the others did. I spent 10-15 minutes searching the internet for what I thought was a rare cut from this artist. When i came back and asked GPT where else I should look it said something like ' I'm sorry, I made a mistake. Thanks for pointing it out. The song "_____" was actually never performed by the band "____". '

To me this is still more reliable than asking the average person a question. Any blog article, youtube video or even news feed can be confidently incorrect. The difference I find is that I expect perfection from computer programs and imperfection from humans.

review:
This app has potential, particularly when it comes to integration with shortcuts. However, as a tool for working with ChatGPT, especially for Plus users, it leaves much to be desired.

Most disappointingly, the app cannot use extensions unless the session is initiated from a web platform, and there's no option to edit your previous inputs for regeneration.

The inability to revise and resend your previous prompts severely limits the app's effectiveness for prompt development since there's no option for an edit/regenerate cycle. If you phrase something incorrectly and receive an odd response, there's no mechanism to rectify it. This renders the app more suitable for casual and simple interactions rather than anything more serious or intensive. 

There‚Äôs also a terrible design flaw that to copy or select text‚Äîthe only way to export your results because OpenAI only implemented Share for the entire chat, and only to give you a useless URL you can post on Reddit‚Äîyou have to pick that mode from a long press menu first. I‚Äôm not sure they were clear that in iOS, Share is the *only* real way to pass stuff between apps, and they just‚Äîskipped it. 

And then these rocket scientists put the ‚Äúcopy‚Äù and ‚Äúselect text‚Äù commands right by the ‚Äúregenerate response‚Äù command. ‚ÄúRegenerate response‚Äù completely jettisons and replaces the prior text‚Äîwith no confirmation.

I can‚Äôt tell you how many times I‚Äôve erased what I was trying to copy so I could save it. That also erases the whole downstream thread, and you have to risk that a bunch of times per thread if you want to export your response text because this is the only way to do it. Way to throw away my quota.

So this app is useless for the professional work I‚Äôm paying $20/mo for, but it‚Äôs just great for posting a chat full of parody song lyrics to Reddit. And that‚Äôs as far as OpenAI has thought about their costly service.

At home, there‚Äôs the severe issue that if you use the ChatGPT Conversation Shortcut from Siri on HomePod, there‚Äôs no way to end the conversation. They apparently only tested it on phones where you have buttons to push, and not on HomePod, where it all has to be done voice. Any command you try to give the HomePod to cancel the shortcut (Siri, stop) will be answered by ChatGPT (buzz off, I‚Äôm not Siri).

Worse, it‚Äôll just listen forever, responding to any question within earshot, until it decides to time itself out if it doesn‚Äôt hear any words for a bit. If you thought Echo was bad about waking up and sending your conversation to Amazon by mistake, you ain‚Äôt seen nothing yet.  

Whoever designed this paid no attention to user experience, user privacy, or the Apple ecosystem, so I assume it was an intern project or something. I certainly hope they didn‚Äôt pay anyone for this because I‚Äôm pretty sad I‚Äôm paying them for this.  

OpenAI needs to step up their game if they‚Äôre going to sell access to end users for $20(!!!!!) a month. This app doesn‚Äôt cut it, and they should be at least a little ashamed it‚Äôs this mediocre after taking so long to develop it.
title: Not very good, and a bit insulting for $20/mo

review:
Either the limit for API calls to GPT4 are too low or something about the app causes it to often get stuck cooking up a response. 

It is very common for me to have to close the app, reopen it, open history, reopen the last conversation, and then ask the same question I asked before the app got stuck.

I used to wait for like 10 seconds before going through this. Now I've learned that if it takes more than three seconds to output anything, that likely won't change at 10 seconds, 20 seconds, etc.

Word to the wise: Respond to any delay that's not due to a poor signal by closing and reopening the app. Can't wait for this to change.

That said, AMAZING app for studying a new technology. Imagine the best professor you had in college (or best high school teacher) and then imagine being able to ask them as many probing questions as you want without feeling like you're being annoying or delaying the lecture. Also, speaking of lectures, I think it's easier for me to remember details of a conversation (active) than a lecture or YouTube tutorial (passive). Truly fascinating.

review:
There are less features than the web version of ChatGPT. (This review doesn‚Äôt speak for subscription versions.)

1. You cannot go back and edit prompts in a conversation. 
2. You cannot clear conversations.
3. Light/Dark theme is system based, there is no toggle.
4. No ‚ÄúChat History & Training‚Äù Setting in the settings.
5. No examples/capabilities/limitations in the background of a new chat.

That‚Äôs all  the features not present on the mobile version that I could find.
Some features that are new or different are:

1. A ‚ÄúHaptic feedback‚Äù Setting
2. The box ChatGPT puts code, ascii, etc. is instead in a patch of tinted background.
3. Speech-to-Text.

Overall, not much is new/different. Some features from the web version are missing however. It‚Äôs ChatGPT however, so it gets 5 ‚≠êÔ∏è. I would personally use the web version over the app as of now. This review doesn‚Äôt speak for the subscription features.

P.S. Have a good day everyone!

review:
The ChatGPT iOS app is an outstanding product. Its seamless functionality and user-friendly interface provide an exceptional user experience. The AI‚Äôs proficiency in maintaining a conversational flow and its ability to comprehend and generate accurate responses is truly commendable.

However, I believe there is scope for improvement to make this great app even better. Firstly, it would be immensely beneficial to add a browsing feature. This would enable users to quickly cross-reference information within the app, enriching the overall user experience.

Secondly, supporting plug-ins would greatly increase the app‚Äôs versatility. It would allow users to customize their experience and adapt the app to a wider range of applications.

Lastly, incorporating a code interpreter would be a game-changer. This feature could aid users in debugging code, learning new programming languages, or even automating tasks.

In summary, ChatGPT is an excellent app that has revolutionized communication with AI. With a few enhancements, I believe it has the potential to become an indispensable tool for a vast array of users. Looking forward to seeing these updates soon!
